# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alex-van-warmerdam
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The **66th Cannes Film Festival** took place from 15 to 26 May 2013.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] American filmmaker Steven Spielberg was the Jury President for the main competition.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The French film *Blue Is the Warmest Colour* won the Palme d'Or.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] In an unprecedented move, along with the director, Abdellatif Kechiche, the Jury decided to take "the exceptional step" of awarding the film's two main actresses, Adèle Exarchopoulos and Léa Seydoux, with the Palme.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The festival poster featured the real-life couple and Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward kissing during the shooting of *A New Kind of Love*.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] French actress Audrey Tautou hosted the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] On the occasion of *100 Years of Indian Cinema*, India was an Official Guest Country at the 2013 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] Seven Indian feature films were premiered among various sections on the festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] Actress Vidya Balan was one of the Jury members for the Main Competition of the festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The first Incredible India *Exhibition*, a joint participation of the Ministry of Tourism and Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Republic of India was inaugurated by Indian delegate Chiranjeevi.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The festival opened with *The Great Gatsby* by Baz Luhrmann, and closed with *Zulu* by Jérôme Salle.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] indicates film eligible for the Caméra d'Or as directorial debut feature.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The Cinéfondation section focuses on films made by students at film schools.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The following 18 entries (14 fiction films and 4 animation films) were selected, out of 1,550 submissions from 277 different schools.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] One-third of the films selected represented schools competing for the first time.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] It was also the first time for a Chilean film to be selected in Cinéfondation.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The Festival uses Cannes Classics to place the spotlight on rediscovered or restored masterworks from the past, or ones that have been re-released in theatres or on DVD.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The Cinéma de la Plage is a part of the Official Selection.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The outdoors screenings at the beach cinema of Cannes are open to the public.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The line-up for the Critics' Week was announced on 22 April at the section's website.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The line-up for the Directors' Fortnight was announced at a press conference on 23 April with the following films being selected.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The French film *Blue Is the Warmest Colour*, directed by Abdellatif Kechiche, won the Palme d'Or.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] In a first for the competition, the jury decided to award the Palme d'Or to Kechiche and the actresses who star in the film: Adèle Exarchopoulos and Léa Seydoux.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] *Blue Is the Warmest Colour* is a coming-of-age film that tells the story of a lesbian relationship between a 15-year-old girl and an older woman.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] It has shocked some critics with its graphic and controversial sex scenes.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] A reporter for the Radio France Internationale stated that Kechiche paid tribute to the "Tunisian revolution" and "the right to love freely" during his acceptance speech.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] The president of the jury, Steven Spielberg, said "The film is a great love story ...
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/2013-cannes-film-festival] We were absolutely spellbound by the two brilliant young actresses, and the way the director observed his young players." The Grand Prix was won by the Coen brothers's *Inside Llewyn Davis*, while Bruce Dern and Bérénice Bejo were awarded Best Actor and Best Actress respectively.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel is a 31-year-old man who still lives with his parents.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Due to agoraphobia, he hasn't been out for over 10 years, much to the chagrin of his father, Victor.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] On the other hand, he gets spoiled by his mother, Duif.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] He spends most of his days spying on the neighbors, setting up his parents against each other, knowingly or unknowingly, and fruitlessly trying to cut flies in two with an enormous pair of scissors.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] His father enlists a psychiatrist who deduces the cause of problems are the parents' unhealthy relation with Abel.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] He then summons a mesmerist who gets frustrated by Abel.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Victor then tries to set up his son with a girl in his theater society, it too fails.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] After a lot of planning, the mother and son secretly buy a TV set against Victor's wishes.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] When Victor discovers this deception he gets furious and runs his son out on to the streets.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel meets Zus, who works at a peepshow called "De Naakte Meisjes" (The naked girls).
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] She takes pity on him and starts a relation with him.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel finds out Zus has a relationship with a married man and it turned out to be his own father.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] In the meantime, his mother finds out Abel's whereabouts and informs her husband.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] When Victor knows his Son is in a relationship with his favoured prostitute, he becomes enraged and goes into a psychotic fit.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] A confrontation with Abel and his parents takes place at Zus' place.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] His son informs Duif that Victor had an extramarital affair with Zus.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Though when she finds neither her beloved son or husband takes her seriously, she calms down and finally leaves her son with the prostitute and takes her husband home.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Finally Abel laughs at all this with Zus and cuts a fly into two with his scissors.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel was van Warmerdam's directional debut.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] He at first planned to make the movie in black and white but others discouraged this and he chose colour instead.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] The vast majority of the movie is situated in a fictive kind of Dutch fifties.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel had over 300 000 viewers at its premiere, and it received a Gouden Kalf for 'Best film' and a Gouden Kalf for 'Best director'.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] In 1990 the tragedic comedy was named Best Dutch Film of the eighties by the Kring van Nederlandse Journalisten.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/abel-1986-film] Abel was produced in collaboration with Orkater and the VPRO.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] Agresti is best known in the United States for his feature *Valentín*, the story of a young boy who dreams of becoming an astronaut while attempting to better the bewildering world around him.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] Agresti's other films include *El viento se llevó lo que* ("Wind with the Gone"), *Un mundo menos peor* ("A Less Bad World"), *El acto en cuestion* ("The Act in Question") and *Buenos Aires Vice Versa*.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] *El Viento se llevó lo qué* tells the story of a Buenos Aires cab driver who goes to an isolated village where the only contact with the outside world is through movies.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] The film garnered the Golden Seashell at the San Sebastián Film Festival, a Silver Hugo at the Chicago International Film Festival, two awards at the Havana Film Festival and a Golden Tulip at the Istanbul International Film Festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] *Un mundo menos peor* premiered at the 2004 Venice Film Festival and was awarded the "Award of the City of Rome" Best Film prize.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] Born in 1961, Agresti made his directorial debut while still a teenager with 1978's *El zoológico y el cementerio*, a short film he shot on weekends while working as a TV director in Buenos Aires.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] Longing to broaden his horizons, he immigrated to the Netherlands, where he exhibited *El hombre que ganó la razón* at the International Film Festival of Rotterdam in 1986.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] In 2006, his film *The Lake House* was released and became a box office success, lending Agresti worldwide recognition.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] He directed his first feature film in seven years, the comedy *No somos animales* (2013), which is a coproduction of Argentina and United States.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] The film stars John Cusack, who co-wrote the screenplay with Agresti.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] Paul Hipp co-stars, and Al Pacino is featured in a cameo.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alejandro-agresti] In 2016 he released *Mecánica popular*, an Argentine comedy-drama film he wrote and directed, starring Alejandro Awada and Patricio Contreras.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] Van Warmerdam was born in Haarlem, a city in the province of North Holland in the Netherlands.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] He was cofounder of the theatre group Hauser Orkater (which later became the musictheatre group Orkater).
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] In 1980, he founded the theatre group De Mexicaanse Hond (The Mexican Dog), together with his brother Marc van Warmerdam.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] This is the name under which all the shows since 1989 have been released.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] He made his first feature film in 1986: *Abel*.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] He plays a role in each of his films so far, with the exception of Grimm (2003).
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] Alex van Warmerdam is married to Dutch actress Annet Malherbe, who plays parts in most of his films and also functions as a casting director.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] Their son Mees is a musician and has performed in various shows by theatre group De Mexicaanse Hond.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] He won the Nederlands-Vlaamse Toneelschrijfprijs in 1990 and the Taalunie Toneelschrijfprijs in 2011.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/alex-van-warmerdam] His 2013 film *Borgman* was nominated for the Palme d'Or at the 2013 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/annet-malherbe] In January 2012, it was confirmed Malherbe, Kasper van Kooten, Marcel Musters and Jelka van Houten would be the stars of a new RTL 4 sketch show, *What If?*.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/annet-malherbe] Malherbe has been married to actor, filmmaker and musician Alex van Warmerdam, and appeared in five out of six films he directed — *Voyeur* (1986), *The Northerners* (1992), *The Dress* (1996), *Little Tony* (1998), *Grimm* (2003) and *The Last Days of Emma Blank* (2009).
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/annet-malherbe] They have two children — Mees and Houk, who are also actors.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/annet-malherbe] In 2010, Malherbe confessed she had had problems with depression in the past.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/black-out-2012-film] Jos Vreeswijk (Thiry) is a former criminal who wakes up one day before his wedding to find a murdered corpse beside him, and no recollection of the night before.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/black-out-2012-film] On review aggregator Rotten Tomatoes, the film holds an approval rating of 45% based on 11 reviews, with an average rating of 5.17/10.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] An armed priest, together with two other men, drive a hobo and his companions from their underground hideouts.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] The hobo, identifying himself as Anton, then appears at the door of a mansion.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] There he encounters Richard and Marina, an upper-class married couple with three children.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] He claims he knows Marina, that she had nursed him in hospital, and demands food and a bath.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Due to his aggressive behaviour, Richard gets angry and violently beats him.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] However, Marina, driven by guilt and curiosity, decides to help him and allows him to stay in the garden shed, without Richard knowing it.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] During Richard's absence, Anton apparently befriends Marina and all three children.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] He has the ability to control Marina's dreams, so she starts to despise her husband while growing to like Anton.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] One day Anton leaves the family and meets his mysterious team, Ludwig, Pascal, Brenda and Ilonka, who start a sinister plot against the family.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] They poison the family gardener and strangle his wife, then return to the family.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Now well-dressed and shaven, Anton identifies himself as Camiel Borgman and becomes the new gardener.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] He gets the guest room while his team settles in the garden shed, and they slowly take on roles in the life of the family.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Soon it is revealed that Camiel and his team have the ability to control people, corrupting their minds or killing them in cold blood if deemed necessary.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Camiel seduces Marina to the point that she wants Richard dead, while Pascal seduces the family babysitter Stine, causing her to become hostile towards her boyfriend.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] The team also takes the children into the hideout to perform some kind of surgery on them, causing them to be more comfortable with Camiel and his team than with their own parents.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Marina, hoping to be with Camiel, is shocked when he calmly refuses her advances.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] He poisons her later, and both she and Richard are buried under the garden.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/borgman-film] Camiel, his team, Stine and the children then depart into the forest.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] Koole was born in Leiden in 1965 and spent his childhood in Nuenen, North Brabant.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] He studied at Delft University of Technology, where he earned a master’s degree in industrial design.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] As a self-taught filmmaker, he began his career making documentaries for the Dutch television program *Villa Achterwerk*, broadcast by the VPRO.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] Some of his most notable documentary works include *Tommie* (2000), *In Belfast is a Wall* (2001), *Zooey* (2004), and *Gilliard* (1996), which was nominated for an International Emmy Award.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] After several years of producing and directing documentaries, Koole expanded his repertoire to include fiction films.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] In 2012, he made his fiction feature debut with *Kauwboy*, which was a national and international success, was selected as the Dutch entry for the Academy Awards, and won the Best First Feature Award at the Berlin International Film Festival.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] The characters in his fiction films often explore existential and universal themes such as loss, fear, and death.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] In an interview with CineSud, Koole stated that he is particularly interested in the parent-child relationship and the interplay between what originates from the individual and what is shaped by the environment.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] Koole is a co-founder of **Witfilm** (2006), a production company dedicated to innovative, artistically driven films together with Iris Lammertsma.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] Witfilm focuses on creative, social, and youth documentaries, as well as arthouse films.
[src:alex-van-warmerdam/boudewijn-koole] Besides his producing work Koole also coaches’ filmmakers, nationally and internationally, in writing and directing.
